title: Kobaan's MendelMax Opto Endstop Holders v1

description.text:
I couldn't find any suitable opto endstop holders for my MendelMax, so I created my own.
Those are intended for the MendelMax 1.0 kit available from RepRap-Fab, using Jonas Kuehling's X ends http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:18384
upper mounted Z motors, and opto endstops from RepRapSource. In case you want to modify the design to also fit as max endstops, I also include the scad source files.

1) Print the x,y,z endstop mounts.
2) Re-drill, or clean the holes as needed.
3) Mount the opto endstop PCB's to the plastics using M3x15 screws, washers and nuts. Use a washer between the PCB and the plastic so that you keep the same height as the soldered pins.
4) Use M5x10 and M5 t-nuts to mount the Z and Y holders, Y min is at the rear right, Z min at the middle right. 
5) The X min is mounted on the left X end replacing the M3 their with a slightly higher M3x30 screw. You might want to skip the middle PCB screw if it gets too tight. (You may also change the scad file and move the mounting hole more to the left, but you'll loose printing width then.)
6) Mount your endstop flags (in my case I bended some copper sheet into the right positions) at the right X end for the Z stop. The X flag is mounted on the X carriage (I used an extruder hole to fix the flag with a screw). And finally the Y min flag sits on the back right screw of the printing bed.#
7) Enjoy !

license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I designed this stand specifically for a Lenovo tab4 8 with a 1.25mm condom. Other tablets up to about 12mm thick and a flat back also work well.
This is a simple fixed pin hinge design, with an adjustable friction leg. This project requires screws, nuts, and dowels. And some drilling, fitting, and assembly. Further details are in Post Printing..
Makes a nice card holder too..(see photo)

Printer:

Prusa/Lee i3

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.3

Infill:

50% 3 shells

Notes:

1.75 PLA
Print 2 Arms
Print 2 Legs
Lower feedrate for Finger/clip 85-90%, good cooling.

You will need:
2 – M3 x 12mm socket head cap screws with nuts;
2 – M2.5 x 10mm self tapping socket head screws or equivalent;
Two sizes of dowel 1/4” and 3/8”;
2.5mm Hex wrench.
The design hole sizes for the dowels are 9.25mm and 6.25mm. I am in the USA, so I used Oak wood dowels from Lowes. You may need to adapt.
The design holes are somewhat undersize so you can make adjustments to get a good fit. Sand dowels and or ream holes. All joints should fit snug (tight), you can use glue if necessary. The adjustable Leg joint should move smoothly. You can make your width anything you want. For my application I used 5.27 inches (134mm). Cut the 3/8” and one 1/4'” that length. Cut another 1/4", 4.56 inches (116mm). Assemble all parts, and fold flat. Check and make sure everything is right way around. The hinge pin is fixed to the Arm with 2 screws or pins. It is important to pre drill to prevent the dowel from splitting or screw from breaking. The printed pilot holes are 90 degrees perpendicular to inside of the Arm. Set the Arms flat on a table, and drill straight down (use drill press if you have one). For a 2.5mm screw I use a 2mm or #46 drill. Try not to drill all the way through (may damage table). This joint needs to be secured with a pin, glue just won’t do well. You can adjust the tightness of the Leg joint with a 2.5mm hex wrench, which you will need to keep handy. If you misplace your wrench, I have included another part called the LostWrench. You can alter this part and or the Finger/clip to your needs

Yes

Resolution:

Infill:

20%

Notes:

Supports:
May be needed for the nose
Required for the tail and propeller

Orientation:
Nose, Body, Tail and Propeller should stand up on the print bed
Shaft prints flat.

The propeller should probably be printed with the inner side touching the bed. This will require additional supports but will make the back of the blades much tidier as the supports will attach to the front.

Resolution:
I used 0.2mm for each piece except the prop which I did at 0.1mm.

Once printed, test fit each piece. I found the main body needs some sanding to allow it to fit into the nose. The tail should fit into the main body without much difficulty.

The shaft and propeller are likely to require some filing to ensure they fit and can be pulled apart if required.

The propeller may need some sanding to improve the look of the blades where the supports were attached.

Assembly:
1) Loop a rubber band over the post in the nose cone and stretch it through the main body. I had to use a string to pull it through.
2) Slot the main body into the nose cone.
3) Loop the other end of the rubber band over the shaft.
4) Push the shaft through the tail and the propeller. Note the keying in both the tail and prop. This step is a bit tricky if the rubber band is under a lot of tension.
5) Once the shaft is through the propeller, rotate it 90 degrees so it slots into the back of the propeller.
6) Slot the tail into the main body and you're done!

You may need to wind it up a lot to get it to spin as it needs enough rotational force to overcome the friction from the rubber band tension pulling the propeller onto the tail piece.

description.text:
SmartRap Mini 2

An update and revision of a classic RepRap design. Started by Smarfriendz, this design evolved for a few years then seem to disappear. I liked the minimalist design concept and tried to make one. But the many revisions and spinoffs left many confused as to what parts were needed for which version.

So I picked up as many parts as I could find and began to piece it together. When many pieces did not have CAD files I redrew them in SolveSpace and began to tinker. So now all but a handful of parts have new CAD files. These are included in the zip file.

SolveSpace is free, open, and small. http://solvespace.com/index.pl

The "version 2" here uses an E3Dv6 clone hotend, fishing line, RAMPS 1.4 and linear bearings on steel rods. GT2 parts are included.

This printer is a nice design, unheated bed, about 50mm/s maybe 60mm/s with good tuning. It is easily expanded to take a heated bed if you upgrade the power supply.

The design here will yield a plate printed area of 160mmx220mmx200mm.
Fishing line limits the max plate to 220x220x200mm. GT2 belt will allow for larger sizes.

Find more info, parts and lists on my website, https://sites.google.com/view/orbitalair/home

I am also on RepRap Forums.

The stl files in download are plates, the zip file contains plates and all individual stl parts and cad files.

These are files for use on a piece of 2 inch PVC pipe to convert a Nerf Jyn Erso or Deluxe Cassian Andor blaster into a rebel A300.

Then tape the sheets onto your pipe with "FRONT HALF" towards the muzzle. You might not need the rear-most set of holes but drill all of the other holes.

I designed in Inventor a new FanDuct for my tarantula, because the one I had before: https: //www.thingiverse.com/thing: 2368133
It was very difficult to print by the thin thickness of the ducts and when printed on PLA it softened by the 245 ° nozzle temperatures. I decided to make a new one with more thickness and ducts that get closer to the nozzle and do not touch the block, in addition to the smaller apertures for a greater flow of air and the right direction so that the nozzle does not cool and thus prevent the temperature from lowering. title: Bibo enhanced bed clamps
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Redesigned bed clamps for the Bibo2 Laser Touch X (and similar) printers-- easier to assemble than originals, and hold heat bed and glass more firmly together as well. Included in the print are bolt covers for the opposite contact points of the glass bed, as well as some simple bed clips for custom bed fastening.

Assemble as in photos, or refer to post-printing instructions for details.

Printed in PLA these are good for bed temps of about 75 C or below. As @VladimirKHV mentions, these will fail at higher (80+ C) bed temperatures. As shown in photos, my white PLA clamps eventually deformed at higher bed temps. They still did a good job for quite some time at 60C bed temp.

My clamps printed using PETG with 100% infill (in photo printed w/red PETG, on Amazon http://a.co/hhiR7aS) will hopefully withstand higher temps.

Version 2 changes:

  • reinforcement around top clamp mounting hole to reduce deformation at higher bed temps.
  • Bottom clamp hole for threading screw has new inserts to provide tighter threading.

Printer:

Bibo 2 Laser Touch X

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.15mm

Infill:

20%-100%

Notes:

Printed from Cura

-- Recommended --
Material: PETG (for higher bed temps)
Print temp: 255
Bed temp: 65
Infill: 100%
Build plate adhesion: None for clamps, brim (5mm) for clips

-- Original (lower temp resilience) --
Material: PLA (for bed temps < 80C), HIPS, PETG, ABS for higher bed temps.
Print temp: 200
Bed temp: 60
Build plate adhesion: Brim, 5mm
(all other settings standard)
Most typical print settings with layer thickness of 0.15mm or less should be fine.

Prep for installation

TL; DR: use screws from original clamps to assemble as in photos. The tiny nut on the bottom of the original bed clamp is not needed-- the screw threads directly into the bottom clamp and is much easier to assemble.

Detailed instructions:

  • Trim off any excess brim or adhesion material.

  • Make sure holes through top plate allow bolts to slide freely (the bottom plate should tightly self-thread when the bolt is screwed into the bottom plate, but the top plate holes are larger and should pass the bolts without needing to turn them). If the top plate holes are too tight, gently enlarge by hand with a 7/64" drill bit or tapered tweezers.

  • Assemble the bed spring bolt with washer, spring, and nut as in the photos: insert washer into slot in top plate, insert nut on other end of spring slot, insert the spring in between, then pass the long bolt through the top plate, washer, and spring, and thread into the nut until the head of the long bolt is nearly in contact with the top plate (do not tighten-- the nut should remain on the far end of the spring slot from the washer).

  • Hold top and bottom plates on opposite sides of the print bed with the hole centered over the hole in the print bed. Insert bolt from top and tighten (do not over-tighten-- bottom plate may strip if tightened too much). Note that the original nut on the bottom of the bed plate is no longer required-- the new bottom plate replaces the nut.

  • Optional: attach movable clip with an additional bolt, placing the tapered side of the clip into the countersink hole and passing the bolt down through the clip, top plate, and screwing into the bottom plate.

  • Optional: [Do not press down on the bed] pinch the hexagonal bolt covers over the top of the two bolt heads on the end of the bed opposite the clamps [do this by placing the hex cover on top and pinching with thumb and forefinger on the bottom wingnut and on top of the hex cover]. These can help prevent chipping your bed glass on the bolt heads. Note that the printed hex covers are not symmetrical. The tighter side should face down. It should snap over the top of the bolt head. Again, pinch-- do not press down on the bed.

General design process

Measured original bed clamps with calipers (dimensions, hole spacing).
Laid out in 3D software using primarily standard shapes (boxes, cylinders, tubes), booleans, and the occasional direct poly/vertex edit.
It took a few iterations of printing to finalize on the design (new clamping style rather than original top-only design) and get correct hole sizing.

Special: in order to get both a good contact surface and good clip precision I print this model upside-down with ball connectors facing the print bed. This results in quite a bit of support material, but the clips turn out better.

  • support density can be low (10%)
  • enable support roof, I use 0.75mm roof thickness, 0.2mm support top distance, and a larger 1mm support xy distance. This lets you more easily remove the support while still getting a nice flat contact surface.
    The included cura .3mf specifies these settings (and has 2 couplers arranged with ball connectors facing the bed).

It took a lot of iterating to get both the coupling fitting well and the clips fitting most tubes (not too tight, not too loose). The tubes vary quite a bit, which makes this even more challenging.
The design posted here has fairly strong reinforced ball posts for locking, slightly recessed areas to allow flex when locking, and fins arranged for easier unlocking with a small pinch.
The clips that attach to the tube have been spaced to provide quite a bit of flex for clamping onto larger tubes while remaining small enough to still hold when clamping onto smaller tubes. Clip details (edge angles, small raised bumps, etc.) also help accommodate different tube sizes.

title: Overhead Filament Reel Supports for Anet A8

description.text:
These are overhead filament reel supports for the Anet A8 printer.

They are easy to fit, and require an 8mm diameter rod to connect them, 300mm length. You will also need to print hubs to support the reels - COMING SOON!

8mm stainless rod is best, although you can use cheaper, 'BZP' or plain steel rod.

You will need to drill two small holes, one in each top plate, this is fairly easy and doesn't require much disassembly.

No

0.3mm

50%

Notes:

Print them lying down, flat side to the bed. Obviously.

Mounting

Remove one top plate, hold the reel support in place and drill a 4mm hole through the acrylic, using the lug as a guide. Put an M4 bolt through and secure it with a nut. Replace the top plate, repeat for the other side.

For the retainers, push an M4 half-nut into the slot and screw in an M4 screw. This will grip the rod and prevent the reels from 'walking' off the end.

You can place one retainer either end, or, as I have done, place both one end, either side of the upright. This way it's easier to remove/replace reels.

title: Better Bike Light Holder for Threadless Stem

description.text:
A centered light holder for threadless (A-head) stems. Small print and an extremely simple attachment system. The holder is attached with a single piece of bungee cord that keeps both the light and the holder in place. The grooved version is exactly the same, but I added grooves for better friction between light and holder.

This is made specifically to fit my bike, but it is pretty versatile and should fit other stems as well. The stem angle has to be roughly correct, though, so you might want to check that before printing. It's not very difficult for me to create a new version with a different angle, so post a message with what you need, and I'll see what I can do!

Specs
Light diameter: 28 mm (I'm sure it will work if it's not exactly the same)
Angle between stem and horizontal: 31°
Bungee cord diameter: max 4 mm (holes are 4.5 mm)
Material: recommend flexible filament to avoid rattle

Note: I haven't got my settings for printing TPU filament right yet, that's why it looks so bad in the pics. The ooze and stringing doesn't affect functionality, though.

Installation

Place the holder on top of your stem. Thread the bungee cord through the holes and around the handlebars, and adjust the tightness with the light in place. Tie a knot. Ideally, the cord should keep the holder loosely in place with no light, and then be pretty tight with the light attached.

Please post a Make if you make this!

title: Tevo Tarantula Y carriage strengthened arms

description.text:
This is a remix of the arms from this y carriage, you'll need all other parts from it to complete the assembly.

I had a lot of trouble getting these arms to print correctly because of the little useless elevated part on the tip where the spring rests. So I removed it.

All the holes in them were making them very weak, so I filled them all up as well. Now they are truly stronger than the original.

Now you can print it upside-down without any support, and have a lot of control over how sturdy they are using the infill amount.

I printed mines in PETG at 25% infill, but if you are printing in PLA, be sure to use 100% infill.

note: Please excuse the pictures quality, I had the resolution to a wrong setting when I took them.

Edit: I added the "v4" arms, which are a simple modification I made to strenghten them even further. however I have not printed those, since the V3 worked just fine, but they did seem to possibly be weak at the center of the curve. So I removed the curve on one side and made it square, now they shouldn't flex at all.

remixed_from.title: Useless Box for Tower Pro Servo

description.text:
I wanted an easier to make Useless Box design that worked without a micro controller. I wanted less parts, construction, and screws. Easier to print parts than existing designs. I used the two remixed sources as a base to redesign the whole thing. I also wanted a paw to push the switch back and "NOPE" in the case top.

What you need

  • 1x Printed Box with battery holder OR no battery holder. If you choose the box without then you will need to use another battery/power solution. My design gets by, but you might prefer to use something else. You can get AAA dual battery holders for cheap in packs of 5, 10+

  • 1x Printed Top-Main with text OR not depending on your preferred appearance
  • 1x Printed Top-Secondary
  • 1x Printed Arm
  • 1x Printed Arm-Paw
  • (Optional) 1x Printed Nope-Text to insert into text cutout in Top-Main-With-Text
  • 1x Tower Pro SG90 9G Micro Servo (cheap on eBay and Amazon)
  • 1x 6pin On-On Micro Toggle Switch
  • 1x Micro Roller Lever Arm Open Close Limit Switch (KW12-3 PCB Microswitch is what I bought)
  • 2x AAA batteries
  • Wire
  • Super Glue
  • 6x M2.5x10 screws
  • 2x M1.6x10 screws (approximate size, this is for the microswitch which has very small screw holes. You could also just superglue the switch)
  • Solder and soldering gun

Instructions

Modify your Tower Pro SG90 9G Micro Servo

There are lots of complicated instructions out there about soldering resistors and cutting the gear piece that stops it from turning 360. Skip that.

  • Open the back of the servo
  • Desolder the wires to the motor and the long wires from the circuit board.
  • Toss the circuit board
  • Solder the long wires you reclaimed directly to the motor (see picture)
  • Screw the back of the servo on

Why don't I need to make the servo go 360? Because the arm is designed to operate within the servo's restricted radius.

WARNING: If you send power to the servo after this mod and the servo has hit its radius limit the servo will heat up and eventually die.

Modify your On-On Micro Toggle Switch (Optional)

Some On-On switches are really stiff. You really have no idea ordering them as far as I can tell. If the servo doesn't have enough torque to push the switch you will need to modify it by bending the the outer casing up and cutting the switch pin down by 2-4 mm. If you get a cheap plastic one then be happy it's not that hard. I got a fancy metal spring one which was a pain to cut.

Connect wiring and Align the Servo with the Arm

Once everything is wired test and the following should happen:

  • When the On-On switch is back (away from the servo) the servo should spin counter clockwise.
  • The servo should STOP spinning counter clockwise when the micro lever roller arm is depressed.
  • When the On-On switch is forward (towards the servo) the servo should spin clockwise.

You will need to get the servo either all the way counter clockwise or very close then pull power. You will use this as your base point for attaching the arm.

The arm should be pressing the micro lever roller arm while turned all the way counter clockwise.

Glue stuff
  • Glue the paw to the arm.
  • CAREFULLY put a small amount of superglue in the arm hole that connects to the servo gear. If you put too much you will glue the arm to the motor case or worse. Tighten the screw that comes with the servo. Make sure you have the servo rotated all the way counter clockwise AND the micro lever roller arm is depressed when you finalize the arm position.
  • (Optional) Glue letters if you used the top with text.

These printed pieces, along with a 2ft section of 4" PVC pipe, an end cap, a 36" length of flat punched bar, and a few bolts make a processing stage for a 16mm film processing machine.

The film stock is threaded over one of the top rollers, under the bottom roller, and back up over the other top roller. The film can then be slowly pulled through the tank to immerse it, roughly 48 inches at a time, in any chemical solution that won't eat through the pipe.

The "top mount" holds a pair of rollers and bolts onto the flat bar. It then rests on the top of the PVC pipe.

The spacer piece is provided to prevent the free-hanging bottom of the flat bar from swinging, keeping the bottom roller firmly centered in the pipe.

The bottom mount piece provides an attachment point for a 1/4" bolt at the bottom of the flat bar, to be used as an axle for the bottom roller. Corrosion-resistant hardware is recommended for the bolts here, especially a locking nut for the axle so that the rotation of the roller doesn't move it.

In my particular case, I wanted the Low Voltage control wiring coming in the right side, the "mains" power switched from the switch exiting the top (thus the hole in the lid) and the "mains" power for a heated bed (controlled by the SSR) exiting the left side. description.text:
This is CaliCube, the calibration cube!
Unlike the other cube out there that is misguiding people to set the steps per mm of the x, y and z axis wrong, this one is for adjusting the flow rate on your slicing software.
Also it's not actually a cube...

Before you print this, you might want to check if your extruder steps per mm is well configured, but even if you don't bother to do that, it's alright, the flow rate is a multiplier of the amount of filament and the end result should be the same.

Print it with your usual slicing settings and measure it, preferably with a digital caliper. Don't measure near the bottom.
If it's measures are bigger than the labeled distance in mm (and smaller in the 12 mm internal distance), then you are over extruding and you should lower your flow rate. If it's smaller, you should raise it.
By how much? Try 10% per 0.1 mm difference and keep trying from there until you find it perfect.

The 16 mm height of the cube isn't affected by the flow rate and should be near perfect, but might be a little on the small side if your first layer is too close to the bed.

Ideally, you should do this calibration for every roll of filament you use. Or at least for every different material.

description.text:
This is a jig I made for your 80% lower receivers. This fit my friend's Mil-Spec 80% lower and we used this to mill out the lower as well as my 80% receiver.

Read first: The Lower jig itself is not designed for you to drill the holes (It may or may not be accurate). Which is why I made a file called "Trigger Hole Template" which comes with 2 pieces. This is secured onto the lower using the rear takedown pin. Make sure the top edge of the template is flush with the top of the lower (place it upside down at the edge of the table), and mark the hole with a fine tip sharpie or mechanical pencil. Next you should center punch the hole so the drill bit won't slip. Drill it out after milling.

The 80 Depth Checker file is used to check for depth as well as making sure you're milling enough to the side. Mill it out until you're able to push the entire depth checker down. The oval cutout on the bottom of the depth checker is for the trigger hole. Trace it with a sharpie or something before drilling through. I just used a file for that part lol. Manually filed it.

I used a harbor freight 1/2hp router and it was capable of milling out Aluminum.

-Drill the holes last.
-Drill bit needed for the trigger and hammer is a 5/32" drill bit. (I'd recommend going down 1 size and filing the hole manually to make the pins a tight fit.)
-Drill bit needed for the fire selector is a 3/8" drill bit.-
-Ideally, you want the pins to go in tight (duh), if it's too tight, use a fine file or 400-600 grit sandpaper wrapped around a toothpick/Q tip and slightly enlargen the hole.

Milling Depth: Use the "Depth Checker" stl to check for depth. The hole on the bottom is used as a template to drill out the trigger hole. Mark it with a sharpie, and use a drill bit + file to get the job done.
